"""
MKT Context Commentary — Hebrews chapters 1–5 (gap-fill pass)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-hebrews-1-5-gaps.py

Audience: Jewish Christians under pressure to return to the Mosaic covenant framework.
Key decisions:
- Catena method: ch.1 citations reflect Qumran/rabbinic chain-of-scripture argument pattern
- Angel traditions: Second Temple angelology (1 Enoch, Qumran Songs of Sabbath Sacrifice)
- Moses comparison: Philo's Moses as philosopher-king-legislator as the foil for the Son
- Sabbath theology: rabbinic, Philo, Jubilees layers of Sabbath-as-eschatological-rest
- Honor-shame: crucifixion dishonor reversed by divine coronation; patron-client household structure
- Yom Kippur: Mishnah Yoma background for high priest sympathy and personal sin-offering
- Greek pedagogy: metriopatheia, pathei mathos, askesis, hexis — Philo mediates these into Jewish context
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

HEBREWS = json.loads(r"""
{
  "1": {
    "3": "<p>The phrase \"sat down at the right hand of the Majesty on high\" draws on Psalm 110:1, which was the most explicitly messianic text in Second Temple Judaism. Qumran's 11QMelchizedek interprets Ps 110 as describing the eschatological figure Melchizedek's heavenly enthronement. The Psalms of Solomon and the Similitudes of Enoch (1 En. 37-71) develop the theme of a royal figure seated in the divine presence. The Jewish audience would immediately recognize the throne-claim as a messianic assertion of the highest order. The prior clause, \"after he had made purification for sins,\" invokes the Day of Atonement (Yom Kippur) as the background — the annual event in which the high priest entered the Most Holy Place and emerged having made atonement for Israel's sins. The combination (atonement complete → seated) makes the claim that what the repeated annual Yom Kippur attempted has now been done once and permanently.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The citation \"let all God's angels worship him\" draws on Deuteronomy 32:43 in the LXX (and possibly Psalm 97:7), part of the Song of Moses — sung at the Reed Sea and recited in the Temple liturgy. The command that all divine beings worship is set in the context of God's vindication of Israel and judgment of enemies. For a Jewish audience familiar with the Torah's liturgical use, placing this worship-command in the context of the Son's exaltation carries enormous weight: the same divine act that inaugurated Israel's redemption now inaugurates the Son's elevation above all angelic powers. The \"firstborn\" language (prōtotokos) draws on Israel's own designation as God's firstborn son (Exod 4:22) and the firstborn's special status in covenant inheritance.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Psalm 104:4 (LXX), cited here about angels as winds and flames, depicts the natural world as the divine servant-system. In the Greco-Roman world, winds were sometimes personified as divine beings (Aeolus, Boreas, etc.); in Jewish cosmology, the angels were understood to govern the natural elements. 1 Enoch 60-69 assigns specific angels to winds, rain, lightning, and seasons. The Qumran Songs of the Sabbath Sacrifice describe angelic ministers whose very substance is as changeable as fire. The contrast being set up — angels as mutable natural forces vs. the Son as eternal divine throne-holder — would be intelligible to a Jewish audience steeped in apocalyptic angelology: angels, however glorious, belong to the created order.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Psalm 45 was a royal wedding psalm, likely composed for an Israelite king's marriage. Its opening — \"My heart overflows with a good theme\" — and its address to the king as \"God\" (Ps 45:6-7) created interpretive challenges for later readers: how could a human king be called God? Second Temple Jewish interpreters read the psalm messianically. The address \"Your throne, O God, is forever and ever\" becomes, for Hebrews, the climactic proof that the Son holds a divine title that no angel was ever given. The \"scepter of righteousness\" echoes the royal-justice theme of Isaiah 11:4 and the Psalms of Solomon 17, where the Davidic messiah rules with righteousness.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The \"oil of gladness\" in Psalm 45:7 refers to the festal anointing associated with royal ceremonies and joyful occasions. In the ancient Near East, anointing with oil was associated with royal coronations (1 Sam 16:13; 1 Kgs 1:39), priestly installations (Exod 28:41; Lev 8:12), and prophetic commissioning (1 Kgs 19:16). The \"companions\" (metochoi) who are surpassed by the king's anointing would have been understood as the court associates or fellow-anointed figures (priests, kings of neighboring territories). The Psalm's setting at a royal wedding celebration contextualizes the gladness: the righteous king receives celebratory anointing beyond all others as a divine recognition of his moral character.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The citation of Psalm 102:25-27 (a lament psalm about God's eternity versus creation's transience) applies a Yahweh-addressed text to the Son. Psalm 102 was a personal lament, but its cosmic sweep — \"In the beginning, Lord, you laid the foundations of the earth\" — gave it a theological reach beyond the individual's situation. The Qumran thanksgiving hymns (1QH) similarly meditate on the contrast between creaturely fragility and divine permanence. The citation's application to the Son reflects the Jewish practice of reading the divine Psalms as disclosing the Messiah's nature — a hermeneutical move documented in rabbinic midrash and Qumran pesher texts.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The garment metaphor for cosmic transience has roots in ancient Near Eastern wisdom literature. Egyptian \"harper songs\" and Mesopotamian wisdom texts (like Gilgamesh's taunt against Enkidu's mortality) use clothing imagery for the perishable. In the Hebrew prophetic tradition, Isaiah 50:9 and 51:6 compare the fate of enemies and the sky to wearing-out garments. The contrast between the perishing creation and the enduring God appears also in Psalm 90:2 (\"before the mountains were brought forth... from everlasting to everlasting you are God\"). The Jewish audience would recognize this cosmic-permanence contrast as a mark of divine identity, not merely a poetic observation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The image of rolling up the heavens as a scroll appears in Isaiah 34:4 (\"the skies roll up like a scroll\") in the context of God's judgment on the nations. The Revelation of John will echo this image (Rev 6:14). In Jewish apocalyptic thought, the present heaven and earth are temporary and will be replaced at the eschatological renewal (4 Ezra 7:30-31; 2 Bar. 32:6; 1 En. 91:16). The Sibylline Oracles 3:80-90 describe the cosmic reshaping at the end of days. Hebrews appropriates this apocalyptic tradition to make a specifically Christological point: the one who will roll up the cosmos is the Son, whose years will not end — the eschatological judge and the one enthroned above the angels are the same figure.</p>",
    "13": "<p>\"Sit at my right hand\" from Psalm 110:1 is the single most frequently cited OT text in the NT (cited or alluded to over 25 times). Its application to Jesus as proof of his superiority and divine status was apparently a central element of early Christian argumentation. The rhetorical question — \"to which of the angels has God ever said...?\" — follows the catena (chain) method of scriptural argument, in which a series of OT citations builds a cumulative case. This method appears in the Qumran Damascus Document, 4QFlorilegium, and the pesher texts: chains of scriptural citations with brief connecting commentary were a recognized form of Jewish scriptural argumentation that Hebrews deploys with particular sophistication.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>The nautical metaphor of drifting past (pararrōmen — to be carried past one's destination like a ship missing its harbor) is apposite to the Mediterranean context of the first-century audience. Sea travel in the ancient world was high-stakes: navigation along the coast required attention and skill; a ship whose pilot was inattentive could drift past its destination with no way to return against the wind. The image would be vivid for any community in a port city (such as Rome or Ephesus). The call to pay \"closest attention\" follows immediately after the argument of ch. 1: having established the Son's superiority to angels, the author now applies it pastorally — the greater the message, the greater the attentiveness required.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The chain of testimony (announced by the Lord → confirmed by eyewitnesses → attested by God with signs) reflects the Jewish legal standard for reliable testimony. Deuteronomy 19:15 required multiple witnesses for serious legal matters; the chain of attestation Hebrews describes positions the salvation-announcement as legally credible under the standards the Jewish audience would apply. The eyewitnesses who \"heard him\" (the apostolic circle) stand as the second link in this chain — their testimony to the community is grounded in their personal reception of the Lord's own proclamation. This chain-of-witnesses argument addresses communities that received the faith at some remove from Jesus's own ministry.</p>",
    "4": "<p>\"Signs, wonders, and various miracles\" is a formulaic phrase derived from the Exodus narrative's description of God's acts in Egypt (Deut 4:34; 6:22; 7:19; 26:8; 34:11). The phrase evokes the Mosaic paradigm of divine attestation — as the Exodus miracles authenticated Moses's mission, so the apostolic miracles authenticated the salvation-announcement. The addition of \"gifts of the Holy Spirit\" reflects the specific pneumatological experience of early Christian communities; Jewish texts (1 Enoch, Jubilees, Testaments of the Twelve Patriarchs) describe the Spirit's gift to prophets and the end-times community, but the distributed Spirit-gift to individual believers is a specifically new covenant development that Hebrews treats as common knowledge for its audience.</p>",
    "5": "<p>\"The coming world\" (oikoumenē mellōn) was a technical concept in Jewish eschatology. The rabbis distinguished between \"this age\" (ha-olam ha-zeh) and \"the age to come\" (ha-olam ha-ba), with the coming age being the messianic era of peace, righteousness, and divine rule. 4 Ezra, 2 Baruch, and 1 Enoch develop this two-ages framework extensively. In this framework, the angels governed the present age (Deut 32:8 LXX assigns the nations to the oversight of divine beings; Dan 10 describes angelic \"princes\" over nations); the coming age would be governed differently. Hebrews' claim that the coming world is not subjected to angels was a significant eschatological claim within this framework.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Psalm 8's meditation on human dignity — the creature who is almost nothing compared to the stars yet has been crowned with glory and dominion over creation — was an important text in Second Temple Jewish anthropology. Ben Sira (Sir 17:1-14) expands Psalm 8's vision of human dignity. Philo (On the Creation of the World 83-88) reads Psalm 8 through the lens of Platonic anthropology. The Dead Sea Scrolls hymn 1QH 9:14-23 similarly meditates on human fragility alongside divine favor. The crowd response in John 6:42 shows awareness of messianic Son of Man traditions tied to this psalm. Hebrews reads the Psalm as describing not humanity in general but the specific human-divine figure whose humiliation and exaltation accomplish what the Psalm describes.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The tension between the Psalm 8 claim (\"everything put under his feet\") and the community's experienced reality (\"at present we do not see everything subject to him\") reflects a fundamental problem for Jewish messianism in the first century. The Davidic Messiah was expected to restore Israel's political independence, defeat Rome, and usher in a golden age (Psalms of Solomon 17; 4 Ezra 12; 2 Baruch 40). The fact that Rome still ruled, the Temple still stood (before 70 CE) or lay in ruins (after 70 CE), and suffering continued created a sharp dissonance between messianic expectation and historical experience. Hebrews addresses this dissonance not by revising the expectation but by locating its fulfillment in the unseen heavenly realm — the resolution is real but not yet visibly complete.</p>",
    "9": "<p>\"Crowned with glory and honor because he suffered death\" reverses the honor-shame calculus of the crucifixion. In Roman culture, crucifixion was the execution reserved for slaves, rebels, and those deemed to have no social honor — the most shameful possible death. Cicero called it \"the most wretched of deaths\" (In Verrem 2.5.168). The Deuteronomy 21:23 declaration that \"a hanged man is cursed by God\" gave the crucifixion an additional Jewish shame-dimension. For a Jewish-Christian community, the claim that the crucified Jesus was now \"crowned with glory and honor\" required a complete revaluation of what constitutes honor. Hebrews grounds this revaluation not in cultural revisionism but in the divine act of exaltation: God's coronation of the crucified one overturns the Roman honor-system at its most foundational point.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The concept of an \"archēgos\" (pioneer/founder/captain) who goes through suffering ahead of others to open a path was comprehensible within both Jewish and Greco-Roman heroic frameworks. In Greek culture, the archēgos was the founding figure of a city or institution — Achilles as the archēgos of warrior-heroism, Heracles as the archēgos who cleared the way through monster-infested regions. In Jewish tradition, the righteous sufferer of the Psalms (Ps 22, 69) and Isaiah's Suffering Servant (Isa 52:13-53:12) provided the specific pattern: the one who suffers unjustly on behalf of others and is vindicated by God. Hebrews combines these frameworks: the Son is the pioneer who leads through the terrain of suffering-and-death, opening the path of sanctification for those who follow.</p>",
    "11": "<p>\"Not ashamed to call them brothers and sisters\" addresses a specific honor-shame dynamic. In the patron-client society of the first century, the powerful patron who acknowledged solidarity with lowly clients was making a social statement that could cost reputation. The Roman system of amicitia (friendship-patronage) involved the powerful extending recognition downward to clients; the language of \"brotherhood\" (adelphotēs) crossed class lines in unusual ways in early Christianity. For Jewish hearers, the \"not ashamed\" language may also recall Isaiah 41:8-9, where God calls Israel \"my servant... you whom I have chosen, the descendants of Abraham, my friend\" — God's acknowledgment of the covenant people as his own, despite their lowliness.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Psalm 22 was the psalm par excellence of the righteous sufferer who cries out in abandonment and is ultimately vindicated by God. Its opening (\"My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?\") was quoted by Jesus from the cross according to the Synoptic Gospels; its final section pivots to praise and the proclamation of God's name to the assembly. In the synagogue liturgy, Psalm 22 would have been well-known. The citation places Psalm 22's triumphant concluding praise in the mouth of the risen Son, establishing that the same figure who was abandoned (v1) now proclaims the name in the midst of the assembly (v22) — the resurrection-exaltation completes the psalm's movement from lament to praise.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Isaiah 8:17-18 comes from a passage (Isa 7-8) where Isaiah waits for God's vindication while his prophetic message is rejected by Israel and Judah's kings. The \"testimony\" and \"teaching\" (Isa 8:16) that Isaiah seals among his disciples is the word that the present generation rejects but which will be vindicated when events unfold as Isaiah foretold. The prophet's posture of trust-in-the-midst-of-hiddenness (\"I will wait for the Lord who is hiding his face\") made Isa 8 meaningful for communities that experienced God's presence as hidden. The author of Hebrews reads Isaiah 8:17-18 as the Son's own voice expressing the same trust-in-hiddenness posture — the pattern of the righteous remnant who believes and waits is fulfilled in the Son.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The \"fear of death\" that enslaves all who are subject to it was a central subject of Greco-Roman philosophical ethics. Epicurus (341-270 BCE) taught that the fear of death was the primary source of human anxiety and that philosophy's highest purpose was to liberate people from it through the argument that death is simply non-existence and therefore nothing to fear (Letter to Menoeceus). The Stoics addressed death-fear through the cultivation of virtue and acceptance of what lies beyond control. In Jewish thought, the fear of death was connected to the divine judgment that follows death — Wisdom of Solomon 2-5 describes the ungodly who both mock death's approach and secretly fear what lies beyond it. Hebrews addresses the same fear but through a different mechanism: not philosophical argument about death's nature but the destruction of death's power through the Son's own death and resurrection.</p>",
    "16": "<p>\"Abraham's descendants\" as the specific beneficiaries of the Son's help locates the letter's argument within the Jewish covenant-framework. The promise to Abraham (Gen 12, 15, 17, 22) was the foundational basis for Israel's covenant identity; Second Temple Jewish texts celebrated Abraham as the paradigm of faith and covenant loyalty (Ben Sira 44:19-21; Jubilees 17-18; 1 Macc 2:52; Philo, On Abraham). The assertion that the Son's help is directed specifically at Abraham's descendants is not a narrowing of the gospel (Hebrews includes Gentile believers in this community, cf. 13:9-12) but a claim that the messianic promise-fulfillment has its root in the Abrahamic covenant — the same covenant that Israel's entire identity rested on.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The high priest's capacity to sympathize with weakness was integral to the Day of Atonement ritual, as described in the Mishnah tractate Yoma. The high priest spent the night before Yom Kippur in the Temple under constant supervision, rehearsing the ritual actions; he could not sleep for fear of ritual impurity (Yoma 1:1-7). The Mishnah records that the Temple court elders would make the high priest weep and tremble before sending him in, so he would not approach the task casually or presumptuously (Yoma 1:5). The entire elaborate structure was designed to ensure that the high priest entered the divine presence with appropriate fear and preparation. Hebrews claims that the Son's own experience of testing through suffering provides a better basis for sympathetic intercession than any ritual preparation could.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "2": "<p>The comparison with Moses was the most significant theological claim Hebrews could make for a Jewish audience. Moses was not simply Israel's greatest prophet — he was the mediator of the Torah, the covenant, and the entire Mosaic institution. Philo's treatise On the Life of Moses presents him as philosopher, king, legislator, priest, and prophet in one person. The Dead Sea Scrolls (CD 3:12-16; 4QMMT) treat Moses's legislation as the binding guide for the community. For the letter's audience — Jewish Christians facing pressure to return to the Mosaic framework — the claim that Jesus exceeds Moses in faithfulness and honor was not a passing theological point but the crux of the argument about which covenant claims their primary loyalty.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The honor hierarchy in Mediterranean household culture was structured by position in relation to the house itself: the owner/builder stood above the house's occupants and managers. Roman law carefully distinguished the status of the paterfamilias (head of household), the clients who benefited from patronage, and the slaves who served within the household. The comparison of Moses (faithful within the house) to the Son (over the house as its builder) maps onto the patron-client and household-authority structures that first-century audiences lived within daily. Moses's honor is genuine — he was faithful in the house — but the Son's honor as the house's builder and owner is of a categorically different order.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The principle that every house requires a builder, and that the ultimate builder of all things is God, reflects the Jewish theological insistence on monotheism against all forms of cosmic dualism. The Platonic tradition that Philo navigated distinguished between the divine craftsman (Demiurge) and the material he worked with; Jewish monotheism insisted that God was the source of both the ordering and the raw material. The assertion \"God is the builder of everything\" also picks up the Temple theology of the Hebrew Bible: 1 Kings 8:27 (\"heaven and the highest heaven cannot contain you\") and Isaiah 66:1-2 (God's rhetorical question about what house humans could build for him) established the principle that the true divine dwelling transcended any human construction.</p>",
    "6": "<p>\"We are his house\" reflects the transition from physical temple theology to community-as-temple, a development found in multiple streams of Second Temple Judaism. The Qumran community, which rejected the Jerusalem Temple as defiled, understood its own community assembly as the true temple (1QS 5:5-6; 8:4-10; 4QFlor 1:6-7): \"the community council... shall be the Most Holy Dwelling for Aaron.\" Paul uses the same imagery for the Corinthian congregation (1 Cor 3:16-17; 6:19) and the Ephesian church (Eph 2:20-22). The language of \"confidence\" (parrēsia) and \"hope in which we glory\" frames the community's identity as temple-household in terms of the access to God that the Son has opened — the community is the house because it is the place where the Son's high priestly work is applied.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Meribah and Massah incidents (Exod 17:1-7; Num 20:1-13) were the two canonical examples of Israel's faithlessness in the wilderness. Meribah (\"contention\") and Massah (\"testing\") became place-names that encoded the pattern of testing God despite witnessed miracles. Psalm 95 (the Venite, sung at the beginning of the Jewish Sabbath morning service and the daily office) preserved these names as permanent warnings integrated into the liturgy. Any Jewish community that observed Sabbath worship would hear this Psalm regularly and understand its reference to these specific wilderness events. Hebrews' use of Ps 95 thus appeals not only to the text but to its liturgical setting — the Sabbath community is addressed by the very Psalm that frames their Sabbath worship.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The forty years of wilderness wandering was a foundational narrative in Jewish historical consciousness, rehearsed annually at Passover (the Haggadah) and woven throughout the Psalms, Deuteronomy, the Prophets, and Second Temple literature. Numbers 14 records the specific event that triggered the forty-year consequence: the faithless report of ten spies and the community's refusal to enter Canaan despite seeing God's works. Josephus (Antiquities 3.8) retells the wilderness narrative to explain why the wilderness generation perished. Philo (On the Preliminary Studies 163-167) allegorizes the forty years as the soul's moral struggles. The rhetorical force of Hebrews' appeal to the wilderness generation depends on the audience's intimate familiarity with this narrative — they know exactly what \"forty years\" means and why it is a cautionary marker.</p>",
    "10": "<p>\"Their hearts are always going astray, and they have not known my ways\" (Ps 95:10) describes the pattern of deliberate moral deviation from the covenant. The idiom \"to know someone's ways\" in the Hebrew Bible denotes relational understanding of a person's character and purposes — not mere intellectual knowledge but the wisdom that comes from loyal relationship (Ps 103:7; Jer 5:4-5). The accusation that the wilderness generation \"did not know God's ways\" despite witnessing them for forty years is therefore an accusation of willful relational blindness, not ignorance. The same accusation appears in Isaiah 1:3 (\"Israel does not know\" and \"my people do not understand\") and Jeremiah 4:22 (\"my people are foolish; they do not know me\"). Hebrews inherits this prophetic analysis of covenantal unfaithfulness.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The divine oath of exclusion (\"they shall never enter my rest\") was understood in its original context (Num 14:21-23; Ps 95:11) as the most severe form of covenant judgment: exclusion from the inheritance. The divine oath sworn in anger carried the highest possible weight — an oath sworn by the divine name bound the Almighty irrevocably (Num 30:2; Deut 23:21-23). Numbers Rabbah and other rabbinic texts discuss the gravity of this oath extensively. The connection between the Canaan-rest oath (Num 14) and the Sabbath-rest (Gen 2:2) that Hebrews will develop in ch. 4 was not Hebrews' innovation — the connection between Sabbath-rest, Temple-rest, and land-rest was a richly developed theme in Jewish theological reflection.</p>",
    "12": "<p>\"The living God\" (theos zōn) is a divine title that appears throughout the OT as a contrast with idols (Josh 3:10; 1 Sam 17:26; Ps 42:2; Isa 37:4; Dan 6:20, 26). In Jewish apologetics against Greco-Roman polytheism — well-developed by the first century CE in texts like the Letter of Aristeas, 3 Maccabees, and Philo's work — the living God was the God who actually acts in history, as opposed to the inert statues of the pagan pantheon. For a community tempted to return to Judaism's covenant framework, the warning against turning away from the living God is a reminder that the living God is precisely the one who has now acted definitively in the Son — apostasy is not a retreat to an older version of true religion but a turning away from the God who is presently active.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Daily exhortation as a communal practice reflects the rhythm of Jewish community life. The synagogue gathered not only on the Sabbath but daily for morning and evening prayer (Shacharit and Minchah). The Qumran community practiced elaborate daily devotions including communal prayer, study of Torah, and mutual accountability sessions (1QS 6:2-8). The exhortation (parakalein) to mutual encouragement was not simply individual pastoral advice but a community practice embedded in the daily rhythms of the gathered assembly. \"As long as it is called Today\" takes the Psalm's liturgical \"today\" and extends it: every day the community gathers and recites Psalm 95 (or its equivalent) is another \"today\" in which the divine voice speaks and the community is called to respond.</p>",
    "14": "<p>\"We have come to share in Christ\" (metochoi tou Christou gegonamen) uses the language of the koinōnia tradition — participation, sharing, partnership — that was central to both Jewish covenant theology and Greco-Roman friendship (philia). In the Jewish tradition, the covenant people's relationship to God was described as participation in divine life (Deut 4:4; Ps 73:28). In Greco-Roman friendship theory (Aristotle, Nicomachean Ethics 9.4), true friends share in each other's life and character. The community's share in Christ is conditioned on holding the initial assurance to the end — a statement about the nature of genuine participation rather than a threat of loss to those who truly belong. The \"if\" reflects Hebrews' pastoral urgency, not theological uncertainty about those whose faith is genuine.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The repetition of Psalm 95's call (vv7-8 repeated here) functions liturgically — as the Psalm itself was repeated in worship, so Hebrews repeats its key summons within the argument. This kind of repetition with elaboration reflects the Jewish homiletical style of the Yelammedenu midrash and the rabbinic petihta (preface): a text is cited, expounded, returned to for re-citation, and expounded again. The effect is cumulative rhetorical pressure: the audience has now heard the Psalm citation three times (3:7-11, 3:15, 4:7) and cannot escape its force. The \"today\" of the Psalm becomes the \"today\" of the homily itself — the preaching moment is the moment of decision.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The bodies that \"fell in the wilderness\" (Num 14:29-33; 26:64-65) were the physical evidence of the divine oath's enactment. Numbers carefully records that of those who left Egypt above the age of twenty (the military census of Num 1), only Caleb and Joshua survived to enter Canaan — all others died in the forty years of wilderness wandering. The Qumran Damascus Document (CD 3:7-9) cites the same tradition as a warning: \"All those who were brought out of Egypt and fell in the wilderness because they followed their own hearts and did not listen to their maker's voice.\" Josephus (Antiquities 3.14) describes the wilderness deaths in sober historical terms. The bodily deaths are the inescapable historical fact that gives the wilderness warning its concrete teeth.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The equation of disobedience and unbelief (v18-19) reflects the covenantal framework in which trust and obedience were inseparable. Deuteronomy's theology consistently links faith in YHWH's promises with the obedience that acts on those promises; rebellion against YHWH's commands was both an act of disobedience and an expression of distrust in his power and faithfulness. The Dead Sea Scrolls (1QS 2:11-18; CD 1:3-4) describe the apostates from the covenant in terms that blend theological unbelief and behavioral disobedience, reflecting the same integration. Hebrews' community is addressed as one that has \"received the good news\" (4:2) but must combine it with faith — the structural parallel to the exodus generation is that hearing God's word without responsive trust produces the same exclusion.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The summary statement — \"they were unable to enter because of unbelief\" — draws on Numbers 14:11 (\"How long will this people despise me? And how long will they not believe in me?\") as the interpretive key to the entire wilderness narrative. The inability to enter was not simply a punishment imposed from outside but the natural consequence of the posture of unbelief: those who do not trust the promise cannot enter the fulfillment of the promise because the two are structurally connected. This understanding of unbelief's self-defeating character appears also in John 12:39 (\"they could not believe\") and Paul's argument in Romans 9-11 about Israel's stumbling. Hebrews does not discuss why the unbelief persisted despite the evidence but treats it as a warning about the community's own danger of the same pattern.</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "2": "<p>\"The good news proclaimed to us just as to them\" makes an explicit structural parallel between the wilderness generation and the letter's community. The rabbinic concept of <em>ma'aseh avot siman l'vanim</em> (\"the deeds of the fathers are a sign for the children\") held that the patterns of the patriarchal and exodus generations were paradigmatic for later generations. Hebrews inverts this principle as a warning: the same pattern that preceded the wilderness generation's exclusion is available to replicate itself in the current community. The \"mixing with faith\" (synkekeramenous tē pistei) is the crucial factor — the same word of promise must be received with the same trust that Abraham showed (cf. Gen 15:6; Rom 4:3).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The present tense \"we who have believed are entering\" connects the community's faith to present-tense access to the rest. Jewish Sabbath theology had developed in at least three directions by the first century: (1) the weekly Sabbath as a foretaste of the world to come (b. Berakhot 57b: \"the Sabbath is one-sixtieth of the world to come\"); (2) the Jubilee Sabbath of Leviticus 25 as a social-economic reset that pointed forward to ultimate liberation; (3) the eschatological final Sabbath described in 4 Ezra 7:30 and 2 Baruch 73. Hebrews draws on all three dimensions: the rest is already being entered (present), was established from creation (past), and will be fully realized eschatologically (future).</p>",
    "4": "<p>Genesis 2:2's description of God resting on the seventh day gave the Sabbath its cosmic grounding. Philo (Allegorical Laws 1.16; On the Life of Moses 2.209-211) developed the Sabbath theology of Genesis 2 extensively, arguing that God's rest was not cessation of activity (God never ceases to create and sustain) but a pattern of divine completeness that the Sabbath observance participated in. Jubilees 2:1-33 gives the Sabbath its heavenly origin: the angels observed the Sabbath in heaven before Israel was commanded to observe it on earth. The Sabbath was therefore not merely a Jewish ethnic practice but a participation in the cosmic-divine rhythm established at creation — a point that makes Hebrews' argument about an enduring Sabbath-rest fully intelligible to its Jewish audience.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The repetition of the oath citation (\"they shall never enter my rest\") within three verses functions as a proof-text anchor. The rabbinic principle of <em>gezerah shavah</em> (analogical interpretation based on shared phrases) allowed interpreters to connect Genesis 2:2 and Psalm 95:11 through the shared word \"rest\" — Hebrews exploits exactly this connection. By holding the two texts in juxtaposition, Hebrews demonstrates that the \"rest\" of Psalm 95 is the same rest as God's Sabbath-rest of Genesis 2. This is not an arbitrary hermeneutical move but a structured reading of the canon's intertextual connections, the same method employed by Qumran's pesher commentaries.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The argument that \"some must still enter\" the rest depends on reading the canonical story as not yet closed. In Jewish prophetic hermeneutics, unfulfilled promises remained active until their fulfillment. The exile and return (Ezra-Nehemiah, Haggai, Zechariah) had already proven that divine promises withheld from one generation could be received by another. 4 Ezra and 2 Baruch, written after the Temple's destruction (70 CE), wrestle precisely with the question of which generation will finally receive the promises — their audience is the community that must persevere in hope despite continued historical disappointment. Hebrews' audience faced an analogous question: do the promises still hold? The argument from the canonical story (they didn't enter; the promise is still open; someone must enter it) is the answer.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The argument from David's temporal position — that his Psalm speaks of a \"today\" centuries after Joshua's Canaan-settlement — was a chronological argument standard in Jewish exegesis. The rabbis frequently argued from the timing of a text's composition: if Psalm 95 was written by David after the Canaan-rest was already established, it must be pointing to a rest still future. The same kind of post-hoc temporal argument appears in rabbinic discussion of messianic Psalms: that Psalm 22 was written after David's triumphs means its suffering-language must point to a future figure. Hebrews' argument that Joshua's rest was insufficient (because David's Psalm still calls for entering rest) is sound by the hermeneutical standards of its contemporaries.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The distinction between Joshua's Canaan-rest and the ultimate rest was not foreign to Jewish theology. Joshua 21:43-45 acknowledged that the land was given and Israel had rest from enemies — but later biblical books (Ps 95; Isa 11:10; Ezek 37) continued to speak of an eschatological rest still to come, even from within the land. The rabbis noted the same tension: the Canaan-rest was real but incomplete, anticipating the messianic rest. Midrash Rabbah on Genesis (17.7) distinguishes between the rest of the land and the rest of the world to come. Joshua (Yehoshua in Hebrew), whose name is identical to Jesus (Yeshua), was thus a figure whose incomplete rest-giving explicitly pointed beyond itself — a hermeneutical opportunity Hebrews seizes.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The single word <em>sabbatismos</em> (Sabbath-keeping, Sabbath-rest) draws the full weight of Jewish Sabbath theology into the eschatological argument. For first-century Jews, the Sabbath was not merely a religious observance but the sign of the covenant (Exod 31:16-17), the weekly memorial of both creation and exodus (Deut 5:15), and the foretaste of the world to come. The Sabbath marked Jewish identity as comprehensively as circumcision — its observance was the most visible marker of Jewish distinctiveness in the Greco-Roman world (noted by Josephus, Against Apion 2.175, and mocked by Roman satirists). The claim that a true Sabbath-rest remains for the people of God transforms Jewish Sabbath observance from weekly ritual into eschatological anticipation.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The parallel between the believer's rest from works and God's Sabbath-rest from works has a complex theological history. Philo (Allegorical Laws 1.5-6) read God's Sabbath-rest as the cessation of concern with the inferior created world and the repose in perfect being. The Mishnaic tractate Avot 5:6 lists things created at twilight on the eve of the first Sabbath — a midrashic gesture toward the Sabbath as the completion of creation. The concept of rest as relinquishing self-generated effort was not foreign to Jewish spirituality: Isaiah 58:13 describes the Sabbath as \"not doing as you please\" and \"not pursuing your own interests\" — a positive surrender of self-directedness that anticipates Hebrews' broader point about faith as the alternative to human self-sufficiency.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The exhortation to \"make every effort\" (spoudazōmen) to enter rest captures a paradox central to the letter's pastoral strategy: the recipients must strenuously pursue what can only be received. This paradox was familiar in Jewish wisdom literature: \"One who seeks wisdom must work hard\" (Sir 6:37); yet wisdom ultimately comes as a gift (Wis 7:7; Prov 2:3-6). The Qumran community combined intensive study, rigorous communal discipline, and trust in divine election — human effort and divine gift were not opposed but integrated. Hebrews' \"let us be diligent\" is not a works-righteousness call but a call to the kind of active orientation that receives what God promises: the effort is in the direction of faith, not in the earning of rest.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The omniscience of God expressed as the impossibility of concealment before divine eyes was a standard theme in Jewish wisdom and prophetic literature. Psalm 139:7-12 develops the divine omnipresence that makes hiding from God impossible; Proverbs 5:21 states that \"a man's ways are in full view of the LORD\"; Jeremiah 23:24 (\"Do I not fill heaven and earth?\") makes the same point cosmologically. The specific forensic framing — \"to whom we must give account\" (pros hon hēmin ho logos) — reflects the Jewish concept of divine judgment as a formal reckoning (Qohelet 12:14; Avot 3:1: \"Know what is above you: a seeing eye, a hearing ear, and all your deeds are written in a book\"). The exposure before God's eyes in Hebrews is not merely metaphysical but juridical — everything lies open for the account that must be given.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The invitation to \"approach the throne of grace with confidence\" draws on the Jewish tradition of petition-prayer directed to the divine king enthroned in the heavens. The throne-room imagery of Ezekiel 1, Isaiah 6, and Daniel 7:9-14 established the picture of the divine throne surrounded by attendant figures. In Second Temple Judaism, access to the divine throne was mediated and restricted: the high priest alone entered the earthly symbol of the divine throne-room (the Most Holy Place) once annually on Yom Kippur. Apocalyptic literature (1 En. 14:18-23; Rev 4-5) describes heavenly throne-room access as a privilege of elevated visionary experience. Hebrews' claim that the community now has confident access (parrēsia) to the divine throne through the Son's high priesthood is therefore a claim of unprecedented liturgical access — the privilege of the high priest's annual moment becomes the community's constant condition.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "2": "<p>The requirement that the high priest deal \"gently\" (metriopathein) with the ignorant and erring was formalized in the Levitical laws but also theorized in Greek philosophical ethics. The Stoic philosopher Posidonius and later Seneca discussed the virtuous mean between emotional coldness (apatheia) and emotional excess (pathē) — metriopatheia was the Peripatetic virtue of moderate emotional response. Philo (On the Special Laws 1.226-228) uses the same term for the high priest's appropriate emotional disposition. The Mishnah tractate Yoma describes the extensive preparations that positioned the high priest for his Yom Kippur duties — including the specific prohibition against personal grief or excess that might interfere with his representative function. Hebrews appropriates this philosophical-priestly vocabulary to set up the contrast with the Son's own sympathy (4:15).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The high priest's personal sin-offering on Yom Kippur (Lev 16:6, 11) was the first act of the Day of Atonement ritual: before offering for the people, the high priest offered a bull for his own sins and those of his household. Mishnah Yoma 3:8 records the prescribed confessional prayer (vidui) the high priest made over the bull: \"O LORD, I have sinned; I have been iniquitous; I have transgressed before you, I and my household.\" This public acknowledgment of the high priest's own sinfulness was central to the ritual's function as a representation of human need before God. Hebrews uses this structural feature of the Levitical system to set up the contrast with Jesus: the Son has no sins for which to offer (7:27) — his offering is entirely for others, making his priestly service structurally superior.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Psalm 2:7's application to Christ's high-priestly appointment reflects the early Christian practice of combining royal and priestly messianic categories that the OT largely kept separate (the \"messiah\" was the Davidic king; the priestly line came from Levi-Aaron). The Qumran community expected two messiahs: the Messiah of Aaron (priestly) and the Messiah of Israel (royal), explicitly separating the functions (1QS 9:11; CD 20:1). Hebrews' argument that Psalm 110 combines both categories in one figure — the Davidic king who is also a priest in the Melchizedek order — was a distinctive hermeneutical move that cut across the Qumran two-messiah framework. The application of Psalm 2:7 (royal enthronement) as grounds for the priestly appointment shows that the Son's divine sonship is the basis for both offices.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Psalm 110:4's reference to a \"priest in the order of Melchizedek\" was a puzzle in Second Temple Jewish interpretation. Melchizedek appears only twice in the Hebrew Bible (Gen 14:18-20 and Ps 110:4) but attracted enormous attention in Second Temple Judaism. 11QMelchizedek from Qumran portrays Melchizedek as a heavenly being, a divine warrior who will execute judgment and proclaim liberation in the end-time Jubilee. Philo (Allegorical Laws 3.79-82) allegorizes Melchizedek as the divine Logos, the king of peace and righteousness. Genesis Apocryphon (1QapGen 22) expands the Genesis 14 narrative of Abraham and Melchizedek. Hebrews' argument about Melchizedek (developed in ch. 7) therefore engages a figure who was already a focus of rich theological reflection, not a marginal textual curiosity.</p>",
    "8": "<p>\"He learned obedience from what he suffered\" draws on the Greek pedagogical maxim <em>pathei mathos</em> (\"learning through suffering\"), attributed to the tragedian Aeschylus (Agamemnon 177) and developed by various Greek philosophical schools as the idea that genuine wisdom comes through hardship rather than merely theoretical instruction. This pedagogical tradition was not foreign to Jewish wisdom: Psalm 119:71 (\"It is good for me that I was afflicted, that I might learn your statutes\") and Ben Sira 4:17-18 (Wisdom tests her students with trials before revealing herself) reflect the same insight. The combination of the Greek pedagogical maxim with the Jewish covenant concept of the Son's obedience makes the verse a culturally sophisticated claim about the nature of genuine preparation for service.</p>",
    "9": "<p>\"The source of eternal salvation for all who obey him\" positions the Son's priestly work within the category of the OT's salvation-history. The Hebrew <em>yeshua</em> (salvation) — the root of Jesus's name — was central to Israel's identity vocabulary: the Psalms of praise, the Passover Haggadah's celebration of divine deliverance, and the prophets' visions of eschatological salvation all used this word. The explicit claim that the salvation is \"eternal\" (aiōniou) distinguishes the Son's priestly work from the annual cycle of Yom Kippur: the Day of Atonement provided a temporary covering that required yearly repetition; the Son's work provides eternal salvation. The phrase \"for all who obey him\" picks up the covenant-obedience motif: salvation is received through the response of faith-obedience, the same response the wilderness generation failed to give.</p>",
    "10": "<p>\"Designated by God as high priest in the order of Melchizedek\" uses the verb <em>prosagoreuō</em> (to address by name, to formally title) that was used in Hellenistic administrative contexts for official appointments or formal honorifics. In the civic life of Greek cities, official titles were publicly proclaimed and recorded. The divine appointment of the Son to the Melchizedek order is thus framed in formally public, official terms — not a secret or informal designation but a divine proclamation. That this pronouncement comes from God's own lips (through the Psalm's oracle) elevates its authority above any human or institutional appointment. The audience, familiar with the formal process of priestly appointments in the Jerusalem Temple (which had become thoroughly politicized by the first century), would appreciate the contrast with a divinely ordained appointment that no political authority could revoke.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The expectation of progressive theological formation was built into the structure of Jewish religious education. The synagogue system involved not only weekly Torah reading but ongoing study (the bet midrash — house of study — was adjacent to the synagogue in most communities). The Mishnaic tractate Avot describes the successive stages of Jewish learning: at five years old, the Torah; at ten, Mishnah; at fifteen, Talmud; at eighteen, marriage; at twenty, pursuing a livelihood (Avot 5:21). In the Greek philosophical tradition (Epictetus, Philo, Plutarch), pedagogical advancement from preliminary to advanced studies was similarly structured. Hebrews' frustration that the community has not advanced as expected implies they know what advancement looks like — their failure is not ignorance of the expectation but failure to meet it.</p>",
    "13": "<p>\"Unskilled in the word of righteousness\" (apeiros logou dikaiosynēs) uses the language of technical skill and competence. In the Greek philosophical tradition, the <em>apeiros</em> (inexperienced one) was the beginner who had not yet acquired the practical skill (hexis) that comes from repeated application of principles. Aristotle (Nicomachean Ethics 2.1) famously argued that virtues are acquired through habitual practice — the person of practical wisdom (phronēsis) has trained themselves through repeated moral choices to perceive situations correctly. Hebrews 5:14 (the mature who have \"trained\" their perceptual faculties) picks up exactly this Aristotelian model of ethical formation, suggesting the author is aware of and engaging with Greek philosophical frameworks for moral education.</p>",
    "14": "<p>\"By constant use have trained themselves to distinguish good from evil\" reflects the Greek philosophical concept of <em>askēsis</em> (training, exercise) applied to moral perception. The gymnasium (place of athletic training) was the center of Greek civic formation; training the body was inseparable from training the character in the classical ideal (Plutarch, On the Education of Children 11). Philo of Alexandria adapted this framework for Jewish ethics: the wise person's moral perceptions are as trained and reliable as an athlete's physical responses (On Husbandry 160-162). The Qumran community's Rule of the Community describes a similarly structured formation process in which the initiated member's moral discernment is sharpened through years of communal discipline and study. Hebrews assumes this framework and applies it to the theological discernment needed to receive the Melchizedek material — advanced teaching that requires trained moral-theological perception.</p>"
  }
}
""")

def main():
    existing = load_comm("mkt-context", "hebrews")
    merge_comm(existing, HEBREWS)
    save_comm("mkt-context", "hebrews", existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f"Hebrews 1-5 mkt-context gaps filled: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
